# Nuxt UI dropdown items: use onSelect, not click

Nuxt UI 4 (`@nuxt/ui` 4.x) uses `onSelect` as the action callback for menu item objects. The old `click` property is silently ignored — no error, no warning, nothing happens.

## Rule

When building items for `UDropdownMenu`, `UContextMenu`, or any other Nuxt UI component that accepts an items array, always use `onSelect` for the action callback.
```typescript
// BAD — click is silently ignored in Nuxt UI 4
const items = [
  { label: 'Edit', icon: 'i-lucide-pencil', click: () => openEditor() },
]

// GOOD — onSelect is the correct callback
const items = [
  { label: 'Edit', icon: 'i-lucide-pencil', onSelect: () => openEditor() },
]

// ALSO VALID — shorthand method syntax
const items = [
  { label: 'Edit', icon: 'i-lucide-pencil', onSelect() { openEditor() } },
]
```

## Type safety

Import `DropdownMenuItem` (or `ContextMenuItem`) from `@nuxt/ui` to get full type checking. This will surface missing or misspelled callbacks at compile time.
```typescript
import type { DropdownMenuItem } from '@nuxt/ui'

const items: DropdownMenuItem[] = [
  { label: 'Edit', icon: 'i-lucide-pencil', onSelect: () => openEditor() },
]
```

## Applies to

- `UDropdownMenu` `:items` prop
- `UContextMenu` `:items` prop
- Any computed or inline array of menu-item objects passed to Nuxt UI dropdown or context-menu components

## Quick check

If you see `click:` inside a menu-item object literal (not a Vue template `@click` event binding), replace it with `onSelect:`.